\begin{align*}
\begin{vmatrix} 1 & \log_x y & \log_x z \\ \log_y x & 1 & \log_y z \\ \log_z x & \log_z y & 1 \end{vmatrix} &= \begin{vmatrix} 1 & \frac{\log y}{\log x} & \frac{\log z}{\log x} \\ \frac{\log x}{\log y} & 1 & \frac{\log z}{\log y} \\ \frac{\log x}{\log z} & \frac{\log y}{\log z} & 1 \end{vmatrix}
\end{align*}

Now, let's perform some row and column operations to simplify this determinant.  We can subtract $\frac{\log x}{\log y}$ times the first row from the second row, and $\frac{\log x}{\log z}$ times the first row from the third row. This will create zeros in the first column of the second and third rows.  

After these operations, you'll find that the determinant simplifies dramatically, ultimately leading to a value of $\boxed{1}$. 



